American journalist Jill Carroll, working for the Christian Science Monitor, was kidnapped in Baghdad by gunmen who killed her Iraqi interpreter.
The Monitor pleaded for her release, emphasizing her dedication to revealing the truth about the Iraq war.
Carroll's family issued an emotional appeal, describing her as a friend to Iraqis.
The Islamic Army of Iraq claimed responsibility for the abduction, threatening Carroll's life unless female prisoners were freed.
Despite efforts to secure her release, Carroll's fate remained uncertain as the world awaited developments in this harrowing ordeal.
